%N A387614 The Pythagoras number of the maximal order of the field Q(sqrt(D)), where D = A005117(n) is the n-th squarefree number.
%C A387614 Let R be a commutative ring. The Pythagoras number of R, denoted P(R), is the smallest positive integer k such that any element of R which is a sum of a finite number of squares in R can be written as a sum of k squares in R.
%C A387614 Lagrange proved that P(Z) = 4. The Pythagoras numbers P(R) for orders R of real quadratic fields were computed by various authors including Peters, Cohn--Pall, Dzewas, Kneser, and Maass. Scharlau proved that P(R) is always finite for any order R of a number field.
