%F A387614 a(n) = 5 for all n >= 7 [Peters].
%e A387614 For n = 1, the maximal order of the field Q(sqrt(A005117(1))) is the integers Z.  By a theorem of Lagrange (1770), every positive integer can be written as a sum of four squares, but not every positive integer can be written as a sum of three squares (e.g. 7).  Thus a(1) = 4.
%e A387614 For n = 4, the maximal order of the field Q(sqrt(A005117(4))) = Q(sqrt(5)) is R = Z[(1+sqrt(5))/2].  Maass (1941) proved that every totally positive element in R can be written as a sum of three squares in R, thus a(4) = 3.
%e A387614 For n = 5, the maximal order of the field Q(sqrt(A005117(5))) = Q(sqrt(6)) is R = Z[sqrt(6)].  Cohn and Pall (1962) proved that the Pythagoras number of Z[sqrt(6)] is 4, thus a(5) = 4.
%o A387614 (Python)
%o A387614 def a(n):
%o A387614     if n in [2,3,4]: return 3
%o A387614     if n in [1,5,6]: return 4
%o A387614     return 5
